properties.title: M 4.5 - 1km SSE of Pleasant Hill, CA

contents.bytes:
Yesterday's (14 October PDT, 15 October UTC) earthquake occurred in a region between large, well-known strike-slip faults in the San Francisco Bay Area. The Bay Area has a 72% probability of producing a magnitude 6.7 or larger earthquake in the upcoming decades. This smaller earthquake serves as a reminder that earthquakes do and will happen in tectonically active regions, so it is always wise to be prepared.

Defining the exact fault structure on which this earthquake occurred will rely on precise location techniques and detailed knowledge of the three dimensional small-fault geometry at depth in the Earth's crust. The earthquake appears to have occurred in a zone of complex faulting between the northern end of the well-known Calaveras fault and the well-known Concord-Green Valley fault. Although this may develop into a through-going major geologic structure in the future that connects the two faults, at present smaller faults in the zone are quite capable of producing damaging shaking as this earthquake reminds us.
